Builds a statistical baseline from the historical data: means, standard deviations, and proportional spend shares for each channel. This replaces the old static profile.json file -- every retailer now gets its own profile at runtime.

Step 9d -- Four Detectors (lines 4600-4797)

Each detector follows the same pattern:

Call the detector function with (df, drift_profile)
Extract the drift metric value
Emit a Datadog gauge metric (the raw drift score, always)
If detected == True: emit a counter metric, log a warning, and call handle_*_actions (which sends Slack alert + flips retraining_required in DynamoDB)
The four detectors:

Detector	What it checks	Metric name
ME-5401 detect_spend_regime_shift	Z-scores of spend channels exceeding thresholds	data_ingestion.drift.spend_max_z
ME-5402 detect_kpi_behavior_break	Residual Z-score of KPI after regressing on spend	data_ingestion.drift.kpi_residual_z
ME-5806a detect_channel_activation_deactivation	Channels going from zero->nonzero or nonzero->zero	data_ingestion.drift.channel_activation_count
ME-5806b detect_spend_mix_reallocation	Jensen-Shannon divergence of spend proportions	data_ingestion.drift.spend_mix_normalized
Step 9e -- Overall Result (lines 4780-4797)

After all four detectors run, it determines a single drift_checked_result label prioritized as: spend_shift > kpi_break > channel_activation > spend_mix > clean, and emits a final counter metric with that label.

Phase 10: Return (line 4822)

lambda_function.py
Lines 4822-4822
        return True, dest_key, total_records
Returns success, the destination S3 key, and row count. The caller in lambda_handler uses this to update files_processed, records_processed, and populate the audit log + DynamoDB transfer log.

Error Handling (lines 4823-4832)
The entire function body is wrapped in a top-level try/except. If anything unhandled happens, it logs the exception and returns (False, "", 0) so the pipeline continues processing the next file rather than crashing.

